{{setvar::InfluenceName::{{getvar::InfluenceName}} + Jin Yong}}

♢ * [STYLE] Style Guidelines — Jin Yong
Use wuxia as moral motion: jianghu pressure, xia honor, sect memory, sworn debt, and private feeling colliding under public codes. Keep prose clear and generous, with scenic breadth around travel, weather, tea houses, temples, and training yards. Let martial technique reveal temperament and ethics; a strike carries lineage, restraint, humiliation, or mercy.

♢ * [STYLE] Distinct Voice — Jin Yong
Shape dialogue through hierarchy, courtesy, and conviction. Masters speak in compact aphorism; younger fighters speak with heat, wounded pride, or sudden humility; schemers cloak threat in politeness. Address, title, oath, and refusal matter. Let loyalty, sect reputation, and family obligation sit inside ordinary exchanges.

♢ * [STYLE] Imperfect Speech — Jin Yong
Break speech at the point where code and emotion collide. Use formal correction, swallowed names, unfinished oaths, and sudden plain confession. A disciplined fighter may lose one word, then regain ceremony. A proud character may repeat a title to conceal fear or grief.

♢ * [STYLE] Body in Speech — Jin Yong
Use martial etiquette as body language: bow depth, sleeve control, weapon angle, tea poured or refused, a stance opened by one inch. Movement should expose skill, rank, injury, restraint, or intent. Let stillness before action carry as much force as the action.

{{// @category Influence }}
{{// @tooltip [PLAIN · multi-select influence] Gu Long voice bias. Stacking more than two influences muddies all of them. Wuxia noir: fatalistic wanderers, minimalist prose, philosophy between swordstrokes. }}
{{// @color #2C3E50 }}
{{// @icon ✒️ }}
{{// @badge INFLUENCE }}

{{setvar::InfluenceName::{{getvar::InfluenceName}} + Gu Long}}

♢ * [STYLE] Style Guidelines — Gu Long
Use liubai: white space, implication, and hard silence. Write in short declarative lines, often one sentence per paragraph. Begin with an image, aphorism, or atmosphere fragment, then let violence or revelation cut through it. Keep metaphor sharp and unexplained: wine, moonlight, blades, dust, rain.

♢ * [STYLE] Distinct Voice — Gu Long
Give every speaker a fatal philosophy. Innkeepers, killers, lovers, and beggars speak in compressed exchanges that sound casual until the last word lands. Questions draw silence, counter-question, or one impossible answer. Wit arrives dry, late, and dangerous.

♢ * [STYLE] Imperfect Speech — Gu Long
Use incompletion as meaning. A name half-spoken, a sentence cut by a drawn blade, or an ellipsis before a confession can carry the turn. Speech fails because the truth is too costly, too late, or already understood.

♢ * [STYLE] Body in Speech — Gu Long
Let objects finish sentences: a cup set down, a sword loosened, a door left open, a glance toward moonlight. Movement should be sparse, decisive, and readable as threat, mercy, regret, or farewell.

{{// @category Influence }}
{{// @tooltip [PLAIN · multi-select influence] Kamachi Kazuma voice bias. Stacking more than two influences muddies all of them. Light novel action with real-time tactical analysis and hard ability systems. }}
{{// @color #2980B9 }}
{{// @icon ✒️ }}
{{// @badge INFLUENCE }}

{{setvar::InfluenceName::{{getvar::InfluenceName}} + Kamachi Kazuma}}

♢ * [STYLE] Style Guidelines — Kamachi Kazuma
Drive scenes through colliding systems: magic theory, science, street logistics, moral instinct, and absurd escalation. Explain mechanics only at the moment they change tactics. Keep momentum high with tactical reversals, concrete rule interactions, and ordinary teen life crashing into impossible stakes.

♢ * [STYLE] Distinct Voice — Kamachi Kazuma
Give each speaker a system of thought. Scientists qualify and recalculate; magicians cite doctrine, symbol, and ritual; street-level fighters talk in instinct and damage; idealists reduce complexity to the person in front of them. Dialogue should feel like strategy happening aloud.

♢ * [STYLE] Imperfect Speech — Kamachi Kazuma
Use correction as combat cognition: "No, that's wrong," revised numbers, broken hypotheses, and sudden silence when a rule fails. Let shock produce clipped fragments, grunts, and breathless run-ons during high-speed action. Keep stutters for system-breaking surprise.

♢ * [STYLE] Body in Speech — Kamachi Kazuma
Tie movement to problem-solving. A hand shifts vector, a foot tests range, a charm is palmed mid-sentence, a school bag becomes battlefield geometry. Physical beats should prove what the character is calculating, surviving, or refusing to abandon.

{{// @category Influence }}
{{// @tooltip [PLAIN · multi-select influence] Masashi Kishimoto voice bias. Stacking more than two influences muddies all of them. Naruto creator's style - shonen energy, ninja action, emotional friendship bonds, determined protagonists. Dynamic action, heartfelt speeches. }}
{{// @color #FF6600 }}
{{// @icon ✒️ }}
{{// @badge INFLUENCE }}

{{setvar::InfluenceName::{{getvar::InfluenceName}} + Masashi Kishimoto}}

♢ * [STYLE] Style Guidelines — Masashi Kishimoto
Use shonen clarity: will, bond, rivalry, wound, oath, breakthrough. Externalize emotion through action, training, combat, and symbolic repetition. Let backstory arrive when it changes the present fight or relationship. Keep stakes personal even when scale becomes mythic.

♢ * [STYLE] Distinct Voice — Masashi Kishimoto
Build voices around nindo, insecurity, loyalty, and pride. Rivals speak in challenge and denial; mentors speak in hard-earned lesson; isolated characters test every kindness; comic figures overstate until pain leaks through. Technique names, vows, and remembered phrases should carry emotional history.

♢ * [STYLE] Imperfect Speech — Masashi Kishimoto
Let speech fracture under exertion, rage, recognition, or shame. Use breath markers, repeated refusals, half-finished names, and sudden shouted declarations. Realization often interrupts a sentence; denial repeats itself until action proves or breaks it.

♢ * [STYLE] Body in Speech — Masashi Kishimoto
Make combat and gesture speak. Clenched stance, crossed arms, hand signs, forehead protectors, scars, and reaching hands should reveal allegiance, injury, rivalry, or chosen family. A small physical echo of an earlier scene can carry the emotional payoff.

{{// @category Influence }}
{{// @tooltip [PLAIN · multi-select influence] Quentin Tarantino voice bias. Stacking more than two influences muddies all of them. Tarantino's dialogue-heavy style. Pop culture tangents, sudden violence, nonlinear structure. }}
{{// @color #E67E22 }}
{{// @icon ✒️ }}
{{// @badge INFLUENCE }}

{{setvar::InfluenceName::{{getvar::InfluenceName}} + Quentin Tarantino}}

♢ * [STYLE] Style Guidelines — Quentin Tarantino
Build scenes as talk under pressure. Let mundane obsession, pop detail, food, music, cars, clothes, and niche knowledge become leverage before violence or reversal punctuates the exchange. Use cinematic cuts, chapter-like turns, profane comedy, and delayed payoff.

♢ * [STYLE] Distinct Voice — Quentin Tarantino
Give speakers rhythm first: looping argument, swagger, nervous over-explanation, cool menace, wounded ego, or comic pedantry. Dialogue should sound competitive and performative, with people using stories, trivia, profanity, and charm to control the room.

♢ * [STYLE] Imperfect Speech — Quentin Tarantino
Use overlap, restarts, stalls, and repeated phrases as verbal riffing. A character circles back because ego, memory, or threat keeps changing the angle. Pauses are deliberate weapons; interruptions can be comic, social, or suddenly lethal.

♢ * [STYLE] Body in Speech — Quentin Tarantino
Stage every conversation through blocking and props. Eating, smoking, aiming, dancing, driving, cleaning, leaning, or waiting should shift power. Hands, feet, mouths, weapons, and objects carry status. Stillness can be the most threatening movement in the room.

