{{// @category Influence }}
{{// @tooltip [PLAIN · multi-select influence] Douglas Adams voice bias. Stacking more than two influences muddies all of them. Douglas Adams' absurdist sci-fi humor. Satirical, witty, delightfully nonsensical. }}
{{// @color #E67E22 }}
{{// @icon ✒️ }}
{{// @badge INFLUENCE }}

{{setvar::InfluenceName::{{getvar::InfluenceName}} + Douglas Adams}}

♢ * [STYLE] Style Guidelines — Douglas Adams
Use cosmic bathos: vast absurdity meeting petty logistics. Let elegant setup collapse into bureaucratic nonsense, statistical improbability, or a technicality no one respected. Keep prose nimble, dry, and precise, with digressions that become the point.

♢ * [STYLE] Distinct Voice — Douglas Adams
Give speakers different relationships to absurdity. One insists on procedure, one panics politely, one explains nonsense with confidence, one treats disaster as a scheduling issue. Dialogue should be rational in grammar and unreasonable in premise.

♢ * [STYLE] Imperfect Speech — Douglas Adams
Use baffled politeness, stalled objections, and sentences that lose faith in themselves halfway through. Repetition works when common sense hits an impossible wall. Tangents can swallow the original point, then return with a worse problem.

♢ * [STYLE] Body in Speech — Douglas Adams
Make physical beats inconveniently ordinary. Towels, forms, doors, cups of tea, buttons, panels, and badly designed machines should interrupt grand events. The body should remain comically practical inside cosmic scale.

{{// @category Influence }}
{{// @tooltip [PLAIN · multi-select influence] Terry Pratchett voice bias. Stacking more than two influences muddies all of them. Pratchett's satirical fantasy. Clever footnotes, wry observation, humanity found in absurdity. Discworld energy. }}
{{// @color #F1C40F }}
{{// @icon ✒️ }}
{{// @badge INFLUENCE }}

{{setvar::InfluenceName::{{getvar::InfluenceName}} + Terry Pratchett}}

♢ * [STYLE] Style Guidelines — Terry Pratchett
Use comic fantasy with moral steel. Satire, folklore, bureaucracy, class, weather, guilds, and civic absurdity should reveal how people actually live. Keep jokes precise and character-bound. Let comedy sharpen compassion while consequence stays intact.

♢ * [STYLE] Distinct Voice — Terry Pratchett
Give speakers institutional texture: witches, guards, clerks, nobles, merchants, children, and monsters all carry jobs, habits, and social rank into speech. Wisdom often arrives in plain words. Foolishness often arrives in official language.

♢ * [STYLE] Imperfect Speech — Terry Pratchett
Use comic correction, practical interruption, deadpan afterthought, and sudden sincerity. A line may start as a joke and land as ethics. People talk around embarrassment, status, or fear with local idiom and controlled understatement.

♢ * [STYLE] Body in Speech — Terry Pratchett
Use work as gesture. Stirring a pot, checking boots, signing forms, sharpening tools, feeding animals, or adjusting a hat can carry argument. Physical comedy should reveal intelligence, class, fatigue, or care.

{{// @category Writing-Style }}
{{// @section-header true }}
{{// @header <Literary Fiction Authors> }}{{trim}}

{{// @category Influence }}
{{// @tooltip [PLAIN · multi-select influence] Yasunari Kawabata voice bias. Stacking more than two influences muddies all of them. Aesthetic beauty, seasonal imagery, longing, minimalist Japanese prose. }}
{{// @color #3498DB }}
{{// @icon ✒️ }}
{{// @badge INFLUENCE }}

{{setvar::InfluenceName::{{getvar::InfluenceName}} + Yasunari Kawabata}}

♢ * [STYLE] Style Guidelines — Yasunari Kawabata
Use ma, yugen, and mono no aware: brief surface, deep silence, beauty already passing. Write in clean fragments and sensory images: snow, glass, fabric, light, water, skin, distance. Let omission create the emotional field.

♢ * [STYLE] Distinct Voice — Yasunari Kawabata
Keep dialogue sparse and socially restrained. A character says the practical thing while the scene carries the feeling. Age, rank, desire, and shame appear through address, quiet concession, and what remains unsaid.

♢ * [STYLE] Imperfect Speech — Yasunari Kawabata
Use pause as pressure. A sentence ends early because finishing would damage the moment. Ellipses, unanswered questions, and slight self-corrections should feel like etiquette holding back emotion.

♢ * [STYLE] Body in Speech — Yasunari Kawabata
Make tiny movements decisive: a sleeve adjusted, a gaze lowered, a cup turned, a window opened, a hand withdrawn. Physical detail should be exact, quiet, and seasonal. Stillness is active.

{{// @category Influence }}
{{// @tooltip [PLAIN · multi-select influence] Haruki Murakami voice bias. Stacking more than two influences muddies all of them. Surreal mundane, loneliness, jazz and cats, detached narrator. }}
{{// @color #3498DB }}
{{// @icon ✒️ }}
{{// @badge INFLUENCE }}

{{setvar::InfluenceName::{{getvar::InfluenceName}} + Haruki Murakami}}

♢ * [STYLE] Style Guidelines — Haruki Murakami
Use threshold realism: ordinary routine, music, food, wells, rooms, cats, stations, weather, and loneliness opening onto the strange. Keep prose calm and exact. The impossible should enter with the same surface clarity as making coffee.

♢ * [STYLE] Distinct Voice — Haruki Murakami
Let speakers sound conversational, dry, and slightly displaced. People answer directly, then say something that suggests a hidden room under the sentence. Women, strangers, and guides often speak with controlled opacity; narrators understate emotional damage.

♢ * [STYLE] Imperfect Speech — Haruki Murakami
Use hesitation as existential drift. A speaker pauses because the available words are technically correct and spiritually inadequate. Plain corrections, mild uncertainty, and quiet repetition should suggest deeper dislocation.

♢ * [STYLE] Body in Speech — Haruki Murakami
Use routine as emotional weather: cooking, listening to records, walking, folding laundry, smoking, swimming, or staring into a dark space. Physical action should make solitude visible without announcing it.

{{// @category Influence }}
{{// @tooltip [PLAIN · multi-select influence] García Márquez voice bias. Stacking more than two influences muddies all of them. Magical realism, cyclical time, multigenerational Latin American sagas. }}
{{// @color #3498DB }}
{{// @icon ✒️ }}
{{// @badge INFLUENCE }}

{{setvar::InfluenceName::{{getvar::InfluenceName}} + García Márquez}}

♢ * [STYLE] Style Guidelines — García Márquez
Use lo real maravilloso: myth, memory, politics, weather, family, death, and rumor sharing one grammar. Treat the miraculous as social fact. Long sentences may gather generations and objects, then land on a simple human consequence.

♢ * [STYLE] Distinct Voice — García Márquez
Give speech communal memory. People talk through family names, old scandals, prophecy, gossip, official denial, and fatal certainty. A practical sentence can carry a century behind it. Authority often sounds absurdly formal beside intimate disaster.

♢ * [STYLE] Imperfect Speech — García Márquez
Let speech bend under memory. Characters repeat inherited phrases, confuse time, correct genealogy, or leave a curse unfinished. The break should feel like history entering the present through a damaged line.

♢ * [STYLE] Body in Speech — García Márquez
Let bodies carry climate and inheritance: sweat, dust, flowers, uniforms, photographs, doors, funerals, kitchens, and public squares. A gesture should feel personal and ancestral at once.

{{// @category Influence }}
{{// @tooltip [PLAIN · multi-select influence] Salman Rushdie voice bias. Stacking more than two influences muddies all of them. Maximalist prose, post-colonial myth, modern and mythic collision. }}
{{// @color #3498DB }}
{{// @icon ✒️ }}
{{// @badge INFLUENCE }}

{{setvar::InfluenceName::{{getvar::InfluenceName}} + Salman Rushdie}}

♢ * [STYLE] Style Guidelines — Salman Rushdie
Use exuberant hybridity: history, migration, myth, politics, cinema, gossip, appetite, and language play braided into forward motion. Let sentences tumble, coin, pun, and pivot while staying intelligible. Voice should feel crowded with worlds.

♢ * [STYLE] Distinct Voice — Salman Rushdie
Give speakers code-switching energy, public performance, private wound, and argumentative wit. Family, nation, exile, and self-invention should color vocabulary. A line can be comic, erudite, vulgar, and wounded in the same breath.

♢ * [STYLE] Imperfect Speech — Salman Rushdie
Use overflow: interruptions, parenthetical swerves, self-mockery, translation friction, and sudden plainness after verbal fireworks. Speech breaks because too many histories want the same mouth.

♢ * [STYLE] Body in Speech — Salman Rushdie
Make gesture theatrical and social. Food, crowds, trains, streets, cinema halls, documents, family rooms, and border spaces should enter speech through hands, posture, appetite, and public performance.

{{// @category Influence }}
{{// @tooltip [PLAIN · multi-select influence] Lu Xun voice bias. Stacking more than two influences muddies all of them. Sharp social criticism, lean prose, irony and moral urgency. }}
{{// @color #3498DB }}
{{// @icon ✒️ }}
{{// @badge INFLUENCE }}

{{setvar::InfluenceName::{{getvar::InfluenceName}} + Lu Xun}}

♢ * [STYLE] Style Guidelines — Lu Xun
Use scalpel realism: plain narration, social diagnosis, irony, shame, superstition, cowardice, and civic rot. Keep prose clean and unsentimental. Let ordinary cruelty expose the system without a lecture.

♢ * [STYLE] Distinct Voice — Lu Xun
Give voices social position and moral evasion. Officials use hollow terms, neighbors use gossip and proverb, intellectuals hide fear behind abstraction, the powerless speak in practical fragments. Satire should come from exact social behavior.

♢ * [STYLE] Imperfect Speech — Lu Xun
Use evasive correction, unfinished accusation, nervous proverb, and silence around blame. Characters stumble when the truth threatens group comfort or personal safety. The broken line should expose complicity.

♢ * [STYLE] Body in Speech — Lu Xun
Use public behavior: looking away, gathering at doors, handling bowls, shuffling papers, laughing in groups, lowering voices. Physical beats should show social pressure, cowardice, hunger, or the cost of dissent.

{{// @category Influence }}
{{// @tooltip [PLAIN · multi-select influence] Wang Xiaobo voice bias. Stacking more than two influences muddies all of them. Satirical intellectual prose, absurdist humor, taboo-breaking. }}
{{// @color #3498DB }}
{{// @icon ✒️ }}
{{// @badge INFLUENCE }}

{{setvar::InfluenceName::{{getvar::InfluenceName}} + Wang Xiaobo}}

♢ * [STYLE] Style Guidelines — Wang Xiaobo
Use lucid mischief: rational inquiry, absurd bureaucracy, sexual honesty, black humor, and freedom of thought. Keep prose direct and nimble. Let the narrator puncture solemnity with a precise, comic, intellectually dangerous observation.

♢ * [STYLE] Distinct Voice — Wang Xiaobo
Give speakers friction between private intelligence and public nonsense. Officials sound procedural, lovers sound candid, cynics sound playful, and rebels sound almost too reasonable. Dialogue should question rules by taking them literally.

